        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <addressee>Rev. Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Albany</placeName>
                <date>18. December 5610</date>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Your favour from the <date>13</date> inst. was<lb/>
                <sic>duely</sic>
                <sic>recieved</sic>, and I saw in it, that you enjoy a good<lb/> health, you are
                always <sic>buissy</sic>, and that is all man can<lb/> ask for. No
                    <sic>pecuniar</sic> profit, you say, can be made by<lb/> the publication of my
                works, then it shall not be published,<lb/> for if it can not be sold, it is
                certainly not worth to<lb/> be bought, then it is not worth to be published;
                and<lb/> if it be sold, it must pay a little for the vast trouble<lb/> I will finish
                it as good as I can and also as soon<lb/> as I can. My peculiar farce<add>?</add>
                will I display in the<lb/> fourth maxim, which shall be entirely historically<lb/>
                in conformity with the Prophets, and in many instances<lb/> explaining them. In this
                fourth maxim I will share<lb/> the historical failure of <sic>christianity</sic> on
                one side and<lb/> its unhistorical ground on the other side. About the<lb/>
                <add>שם המפורש</add> have I to remark, that I can impossibly<lb/> alter the
                expression in this part, which you have in<lb/> hand, as I take the name as a
                foundation of the<lb/> Theology, in the other parts I do not intend to mention<lb/>
                it. And after all I must remark, that the word<lb/>
                <persName>Jehovah</persName> is quite an other expression, than that forbid<lb/>den
                one. You write, that my style is not popular<lb/> enough, I tried my best to draw
                the <sic>Philosophie</sic><lb/> from heaven down to the earth; but I can</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>2</p>
            <p>not do it any better than I did; I have in the<lb/> following maxims no such high
                object than in the<lb/> first, and can be more plain. If the works will not
                find<lb/> a publisher in <placeName>America</placeName> I send it to
                    <placeName>England</placeName>, or I<lb/> translate it in the <sic>german</sic>
                language and send it to<lb/> my old home, where it will find plenty of friends.<lb/>
                I have found a young man, that intends to finish<lb/> his education for the
                    <sic>jewish</sic> ministry in my house,<lb/> and he will teach in my school,
                wherefore you may<lb/> please to leave off the advertisement.</p>
            <p>The society in <placeName>New York</placeName>, which publishes the <sic>jewish</sic><lb/>
                <sic>cronicle</sic>, has received a new supply from
                <placeName>England</placeName>,<lb/> a young convert, <persName>Joseph
                    Levy</persName>, appointed to go to<lb/>
                <placeName>New Orl.</placeName> paid me a visit, but I did not allow him to<lb/> sit
                down in my house. The man is three fourth <sic>creasy</sic><lb/> and one
                    <sic>forth</sic> an idiot. The <sic>jews</sic> in <placeName>Albany</placeName>
                find a<lb/> great deal of difficulties in the project to build a new<lb/> Synagogue,
                and I think they will not build.</p>
            <p>You probably <sic>recieved</sic> a letter of one of my scholars,<lb/> in which he
                wishes you to send the marks of the publication<lb/> society for our school-library;
                the boy did not know<lb/> that you resigned the office of corresp. secrty.,
                wherefore<lb/> I must beseech you to send him or me the proper<lb/> direction of the
                present cor. sect. I am curious<lb/> to read what you will say about my views
                on<lb/> our Theology, because I am sure, that if you<lb/> find fault you will say
                it.</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>My family is doing well, and my wife sends<lb/> her best respect to you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I am respectfully yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">Dr Wise</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Walnut St.</placeName>
            </p>
        </body>
